logic.description:
The primitive hardware bit type. `logic` is a single bit; `logic[N]` is an N-bit vector. This is the fundamental value type for hardware signals in Anvil.

**Example:**

```anvil
reg flag  : logic;
reg data  : logic[8];
reg bus   : logic[32];
```

int.description:
The kind keyword for an integer compile-time parameter. Used in parameter lists to declare a parameter that takes an integer value.

**Example:**

```anvil
proc P<N : int>(ep : left Ch) { ... }
type Vec<N : int> = logic[N];
```

description:
The kind keyword for a type parameter. Used in parameter lists to declare a parameter that takes a type value.

**Example:**

```anvil
proc P<T : type>(ep : left Ch) { ... }
type Vec<T : type, N : int> = T[N];
```

loop.description:
Starts an infinite loop thread inside a process. The body expression is repeated indefinitely; the loop restarts as soon as the body completes. An optional message specifier causes the loop to restart on that message.

**Example:**

```anvil
loop {
    let x = recv ep.req >>
    send ep.resp(x)
}

loop ep.rst { /* restarts when ep.rst arrives */ }
```

try.description:
A send or receive *attempt*. If the operation can proceed immediately, the success branch is taken; otherwise the `else` branch is taken.

**Example:**

```anvil
try x = recv ep.msg { use(x) } else { fallback }
try send ep.msg(val) { success } else { fallback }
```
